dn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Magnification-Equation.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The equation for calculating magnification can be rearranged to calculate either actual size, image size, or magnification.</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="worked-example"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M3 17.25V21h3.75L17.81 9.94l-3.75-3.75L3 17.25zM20.71 7.04a.996.996 0 0 0 0-1.41l-2.34-2.34a.996.996 0 0 0-1.41 0l-1.83 1.83 3.75 3.75 1.83-1.83z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Worked Example</h4></header><p>An <b>image</b> of an animal cell is 30 mm in diameter and it has been <b>magnified</b> by a factor of  x3000.</p><p>What is the <b>actual</b> diameter of the cell?</p></div></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Worked Example Using Magnification Equation" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="474" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Worked-Example-Using-Magnification-Equation.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><h4 id="using-an-eyepiece-graticule-stage-micrometer">Using an eyepiece graticule &amp; stage micrometer</h4><ul><li><p>A <b>graticule</b> is a small disc that has an <b>engraved ruler</b></p></li><li><p>It can be placed <b>into the eyepiece </b>of a microscope to act as a ruler in the field of view, so is sometimes known as an <b>eyepiece graticule</b></p></li><li><p>As an eyepiece graticule has no fixed units it must be <b>calibrated </b>for the objective lens that is in use</p><ul><li><p>The graticule in the eyepiece remains the same size when the magnification of the microscope is altered, so recalibration is needed at each viewing magnification</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Calibration of the eyepiece graticule is done using a microscope slide with an engraved scale known as <b>a stage micrometer</b></p><ul><li><p>The <b>smallest</b> set of divisions on a stage micrometer usually measure<b> 0.01 mm</b>, or <b>10</b> <b>μm</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>By using the<b> eyepiece graticule and the stage micrometer together,</b> the size of each graticule unit can be calculated</p><ul><li><p>After this is known the graticule can be used as a <b>ruler </b>to measure objects in the field of view</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Graticule Calibration" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="611" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Graticule-Calibration.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Graticule-Calibration.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The stage micrometer scale is used to find out how many micrometers each graticule unit represents</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="worked-example"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M3 17.25V21h3.75L17.81 9.94l-3.75-3.75L3 17.25zM20.71 7.04a.996.996 0 0 0 0-1.41l-2.34-2.34a.996.996 0 0 0-1.41 0l-1.83 1.83 3.75 3.75 1.83-1.83z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Worked Example</h4></header><p>Calculate the size of the units of the eyepiece graticule divisions in the image below.</p><p>Note that the large divisions in the top half of the image show the stage micrometer and that the smallest stage micrometer divisions are 0.01 mm across. </p><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Eyepiece graticule &amp; Micrometer" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="656" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/06/Eyepiece-graticule-Micrometer.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p><b>Answer: </b><br/><br/><b>Step 1: Observe the number of eyepiece unit divisions per micrometer unit</b></p><p class="text-center">In the image, the stage micrometer has three lines</p><p class="text-center">Each micrometer division has 40 eyepiece graticule divisions within it</p><p><b>Step 2: Calculate the size of each eyepiece graticule unit</b></p><p class="text-center">40 graticule divisions = 0.01 mm = 10 µm</p><p class="text-center">1 graticule unit = 10 <b>÷</b> 40 = 0.25 µm</p><p><b>Step 3: Calculate the size of an object using the size of each graticule unit</b><br/><br/>An object spans five eyepiece graticule units <b>SO</b></p><p class="text-center">5 x 0.25 µm = 1.25 µm</p></div></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>The biggest pitfall with these kinds of calculations is forgetting to convert the units so that they match before embarking on a calculation. E.g. if image size is measured in mm but the actual size of an object is given in µm then both need to be converted into µm before using the equation triangle above.</p><p>To convert a measurement from mm into µm the measurement must be multiplied by 1000 (there are 1000 µm in 1 mm).</p><p> </p></div></div></div></div>